      <Notes><![CDATA[  A collaborative research agreement between the Peoples' Republic of China's (PRC) Chinese Academy of Sciences and the United States Department of Energy, signed in August of 1987, has resulted in the compilation and exchange of several data sets that will be useful in reconstructing past climates in China, extending and calibrating instrumental records, and addressing potential CO2-induced global and regional warming.
<br><br>
  This report describes one of the twelve PRC proxy data sets exchanged as part of this bilateral agreement.  These annual dryness/wetness indices for Luoyang and Beijing comprise five grades (1-5), denoted wet, subwet, normal, subdry, and dry, respectively.  These indices may be used to examine long-term precipitation and climate patterns for Luoyang and Beijing and compared to other precipitation and temperature-related indices and instrumental records for these sites.  Song (1990) found that dryness/wetness indices could be used to reconstruct ENSO events to a certain extent.]]></Notes>
